            <Abstract ID="Abs1" Language="En">
              <Heading>Abstract</Heading>
              <Para>Static magnetization measurements on the ferrimagnetic spinels Fe<Subscript>2(1−<Emphasis Type="Italic">y</Emphasis>)</Subscript>Mg<Subscript>1+<Emphasis Type="Italic">y</Emphasis>
                </Subscript>Ti<Subscript>
                  <Emphasis Type="Italic">y</Emphasis>
                </Subscript>O<Subscript>4</Subscript> with<Emphasis Type="Italic">y</Emphasis>=0.3, 0.4, 0.5, and 0.6 show that these compounds have no well-defined orderdisorder transition temperature and that their ferrimagnetism may not be described in terms of the Néel theory. From the Mössbauer spectra we conclude that a temperature dependent number of the ferric ions does not participate in the ferrimagnetism of those compounds with composition<Emphasis Type="Italic">y</Emphasis>≧0.4. The explanation of the observed magnetic and Mössbauer properties is based on the assumption that each ferric ion must have at least two magnetic linkages of the type Fe<Stack>
                  <Subscript>A</Subscript>
                  <Superscript>3+</Superscript>
                </Stack>−O<Superscript>2−</Superscript>−Fe<Stack>
                  <Subscript>B</Subscript>
                  <Superscript>3+</Superscript>
                </Stack> in order to couple its magnetic moment to the neighbouring ones over the entire temperature interval between 0 K and the respective Néel temperature.</Para>
            </Abstract>
